<TEXT>
a food and drug administration advisory 
committee on tuesday unanimously recommended approval of interferon 
alpha as the first treatment shown to be effective against 
hepatitis c an fda spokeswoman said 
interferon alpha a substance produced naturally in the body 
that can be made in large quantitities by genetic engineering has 
already been approved for treatment of hairycell leukemia 
kaposis sarcoma and genital warts 
the drug does not cure hepatitis c also known as nona nonb 
hepatitis and is not universally effective but studies have shown 
that it can alleviate some effects of the disease said fda 
spokeswoman faye peterson 
committee members also recommended longterm followup of 
hepatitis patients after the drug receives formal approval 
hepatitis c is a chronic disease that sometimes leads to 
cirrhosis and cancer of the liver which often are fatal as many 
as 200000 people get hepatitis c each year in the united states 
at least half from unknown causes 
known causes include blood transfusions from infected people 
sharing of infected intravenous needles by drug abusers and 
according to some studies sexual relations 
the drug is manufactured by scheringplough corp under the 
brand name intron a 
the advisory panel also recommended against fda approval of 
granulocytemacrophage colony stimulating factor or gmcsf one of 
a new family of complex proteins that regulate production of blood 
cells gmcsf is critical in the production of white blood cells 
committee members agreed that more research on the drug is 
needed before it can be approved for use in cancer therapy and 
other diseases that have impaired the bodys ability to fight 
infections peterson said 
the drug also genetically engineered is being tested on 
patients whose bonemarrow transplants failed the panel 
recommended the fda allow continued use of the drug for patients 
with this lifethreatening condition 
the drug is made by hoechstroussel pharmaceutical inc 
the body produces gmcsf naturally but in very small 
quantities its gene was identified recently and the drug now can 
be produced through genetic engineering the company said 
</TEXT>
