<TEXT>
the senate defeated republican attempts 
tuesday to diminish labors clout at the polls usually on behalf 
of democrats as part of a bill to clean up the way federal 
election campaigns are financed 
on largely partyline votes democrats defeated amendments to 
strip unions of their taxexempt status if they stay in politics 
and to allow their members to demand refunds of any dues spent on 
elections or lobbying 
republicans claimed the votes demonstrate their contention that 
democrats campaign finance reform bill and its spending ceilings 
is a partisan charade that will assure a veto by president bush 
we might as well as go on to something else said senate gop 
leader bob dole of kansas 
so far this campaign reform bill only reforms republicans 
dole said we like reform but its got to be reform that 
applies to both sides 
meanwhile 16 democrats joined republicans in defeating an 
effort by liberals to have the government pick up 70 percent of a 
candidates general election costs through a new 2 checkoff on 
individual income tax returns 
democrats had stripped the provision from their bill last friday 
but sen john kerry dmass tried to put it bank in tuesday 
night his amendment was defeated 6830 
also defeated on a 4949 tie vote was an amendment by sen john 
mccain rariz that would have prevented candidates from rolling 
over any surpluses in their campaign accounts for use by their 
house and senate offices or for future campaigns instead mccains 
measure would have required that any surpluses be turned over to 
the government 
democrats did go along with one republican amendment by sen 
don nickles of oklahoma to prohibit senators and house members 
from using their free postage privileges for mass mailings during 
the calendar years they are up for reelection 
nickles cited figures showing that uses of the congressional 
mail frank nearly double in election years for example they went 
from 53 million in 1981 to 100 million in 1982 from 72 million 
in 1983 to 110 million in 1984 and from 63 million in 1987 to 
113 million in 1988 
also approved was an amendment by sen lloyd bentsen dtexas 
that would prohibit companies more than 50 percent foreign owned 
from forming political action committees to raise funds for 
candidates 
bentsen whose amendment was adopted by a 7327 vote said pacs 
of foreignowned companies contributed 28 million to candidates 
in the 1988 election a 19 percent increase over 1986 and 5 
percent of the total given by all corporate pacs 
it creates inevitable pressures on us employees to use 
their pac muscle in ways acceptable to the corporate masters in 
london or frankfurt or tokyo he said american campaigns 
should be for americans 
sen mitch mcconnell rky said bentsens proposal was moot 
since democrats and republicans in the senate have now agreed to 
ban pac contributions altogether in the bill 
nonetheless he voted against it saying the amendment would 
strip some 3000 us citizens who work at a toyota assembly plant 
in his state of their political rights should the courts rule that 
a total ban on pacs is unconstitutional 
it does not treat all of us citizens the same way mcconnell 
said if you happen to work at toyota in kentucky you dont get 
the same rights as somebody who works at ford 
on a 5841 vote the senate defeated a mcconnell amendment to 
lift the taxexempt status of unions and other organizations if 
they participate at all in election campaigns 
rejected earlier on a 5941 vote was a republican amendment that 
would have allowed the nations 17 million union members to demand 
refunds of any dues not spent directly on collective bargaining or 
grievances 
republicans contended unions spend tens of millions of dollars 
of the estimated 33 billion to 5 billion in dues they collect 
each year to indirectly benefit their favorite politicians through 
voter registration voter education and turnout programs 
the national right to work committee a group that wants to 
outlaw agency shop contracts under which nonunion workers must pay 
fees to unions estimates that organized labor spends 330 million 
on politics in every twoyear election cycle 
if you dont do anything about this sewer money from unions i 
dont think you have campaign reform said sen orrin hatch 
rutah ninety percent goes to democrats even though 30 percent 
to 40 percent of union members are republicans 
president bush announced a year ago that as a part of any 
campaign finance reform measure he wanted congress to expand on a 
supreme court ruling to give workers a right to seek refunds of any 
union dues spent on politics 
the court ruled in 1988 that a nonunion technician who paid 
fees to the communications workers of america as part of an agency 
shop contract with atampt was entitled to a refund of the portion not 
spent directly on collective bargaining 
