<TEXT>
a grand jury declined tuesday to indict a 
white police officer in the shooting of a black teenager whose 
death this year sparked rioting in the new york city suburb of 
teaneck 
after announcing the grand jurys decision state attorney 
general robert del tufo said he would empanel a new grand jury 
because of errors he said were made in the autopsy 
the grand jury investigated the death of phillip pannell 16 of 
river edge who was shot in the back by teaneck police officer gary 
spath 29 on april 10 pannels death sparked a night of racially 
motivated rioting in teaneck a new york city suburb 
the shooting prompted mobs of angry youths to rampage in an area 
near the police headquarters in teaneck overturning cars and 
attacking journalists black community activists organized marches 
and the killing polarized a community that had prided itself on 
racial harmony 
the dead boys father phillip pannell sr appealed for calm he 
gave reporters what he called a message for the citys young people 
im willing to give america another chance for justice he 
said i feel justice will be served chill out 
after announcement tuesday lawyers from the naacp and community 
leaders met teaneck youths in the parking lot behind the police 
station trying to calm them 
ted wells a lawyer for the national association for the 
advancement of colored people told the teens that calling a second 
grand jury was an extraordinary step 
if there was a scam theyd give no indictment shut up and 
bite the bullet wells explained 
spath met with reporters at his attorneys office and said id 
like to thank the lord jesus christ for carrying me on his 
shoulders weve been praying for the pannell family all along and 
will continue to pray for the pannell family 
the attorney general said the decision that a new grand jury 
probe is warranted is fortified by the fact that the grand jury 
which heard the case was seriously divided 
the attorney general maintained that errors in the autopsy by 
the bergen county medical examiner led to an incorrect conclusion 
concerning the possible actions of mr pannell at the time he was 
shot 
a key question before the grand jury was whether pannell had 
raised his hands in the air and pleaded with police not to shoot 
as some witnesses said or whether he twice stopped and turned in a 
threatening way toward the officers 
the mistake permeated and distorted the investigation and the 
grand jury presentation the medical examiner has admitted his 
error del tufo said 
del tufo said the decision that a new grand jury probe is 
warranted is fortified by the fact that the grand jury which 
heard the case was seriously divided 
spaths attorney robert galantucci accused del tufo and gov 
jim florio of calling for another grand jury to curry favor with 
voters 
it sends a bad message to police officers throughout this 
state it sends a bad message to them but they cant change the 
truth galantucci said they shouldnt be playing politics with 
the grand jury system 
the 21member grand jury was to determine if spath was justified 
in firing his 38caliber service revolver or whether he should be 
indicted on charges of manslaughter or improperly using deadly 
force 
the grand jurors have been meeting once or twice a week since 
late april they reached a decision late tuesday afternoon and 
attorney general robert del tufo scheduled a news conference to 
release the panels findings 
the shooting took place when spath responded to a telephone 
report of a youth with a gun 
the grand jurors heard accounts from more than two dozen 
witnesses including police bystanders and pannells friends 
among those testifying before the panel was officer wayne 
blanco who frisked pannell moments before he was shot by spath 
according to the record of hackensack blanco testified that he 
warned spath that he felt a gun in pannells jacket according to 
the newspaper 
but teenagers with pannell said there was no frisking before 
the youngster ran the man whose telephone call alerted police 
about a youth with a gun backed the youths accounts when he 
testified before the grand jury the newspaper said 
because of the sensitivity of the case it was transferred from 
bergen county to a state grand jury sitting in trenton and it was 
handled by a deputy attorney general 
spath was suspended with pay 
