<TEXT>
navy searchers on monday found debris on the 
ocean floor near where a cargo door tore off a united airlines jet 
last year killing nine people authorities said 
searchers have yet to confirm the debris is from united airlines 
flight 811 said lt col bob anderson a navy spokesman 
one object wedged in the ocean floor is believed to be a large 
piece of metal which could be the 10by10foot cargo door 
anderson said 
the 224foot navy tug uss narrangansett using a small 
remotecontrolled submarine to search the ocean floor three miles 
down recorded the location of the find 90 miles southsoutheast 
the tug was to return to honolulu on tuesday anderson said 
the orion submarines sonar located the debris but searchers 
were unable to obtain a picture of the find with the subs video 
camera anderson said 
the navy will report the find to the national transportation 
safety board which will decide whether to try to recover the 
debris anderson said 
the boeing 747 carried 355 passengers when it left honolulu 
international airport for new zealand on feb 24 1989 
shortly after takeoff a cargo door opened at 22000 feet 
tearing away a section of fuselage nine people were swept to their 
deaths and five others suffered serious injuries the crew managed 
to return and land in honolulu 
the ntsbs inquiry determined that a faulty design of the doors 
locking mechanism probably caused a cockpit panel light to falsely 
indicate the door was locked 
the ntsb blamed united boeing co and the federal aviation 
administration for failing to correct problems with the door 
the national transportation safety board has completed its 
inquiry into the accident but has requested the search for the 
door with hopes its inspection will lead to better plane safety 
</TEXT>
