<TEXT>
no one disagrees that medicare and medicaid 
have helped millions of americans over the past quarter century 
but critics say these two health care safety nets have developed 
too many large holes 
when these programs were enacted many persons expected that 
medicare and medicaid would ensure full coverage of all health care 
services for the elderly disabled and poor said rep edward 
roybal dcalif 
though much has been accomplished there remain many gaps 
and weaknesses in the programs roybal chairman of the house 
select committee on aging said in a report released at a hearing 
of the panel on monday 
with health care costs rising twice as fast as inflation the 
price of private medical insurance is getting beyond the reach of 
many employers are trimming coverage and states are reducing their 
medicaid rolls to cut costs 
though taxpayers spend more than 174 billion a year on the 
programs an estimated 37 million americans have no health 
insurance and medicaid covers only 42 percent of those living in 
poverty and roybal said 200 million people are underinsured for 
catastrophic or longterm illness 
the 25th anniversary of medicare and medicaid which were signed 
into law june 30 1965 provided an opportunity for those who want 
to change the nations health care system to highlight problems in 
the government insurance programs 
but before the hard hitting began roybal and other members of 
the committee marked the anniversary with a large sheet cake iced 
with white frosting and trimmed in red white and blue 
the celebratory mood turned serious as roybal opened the 
hearing outlining the major failings of the two programs 
a national health insurance program is a must for this 
country said roybal who has introduced a bill that would build 
medicare into a federally based nationwide program covering health 
and longterm care 
the bipartisan pepper commission 12 members of congress and 
three white house appointees has proposed building on the 
existing employerprovided insurance system and improving and 
expanding the medicaid program 
sen jay rockefeller dwva chairman of the pepper 
commission said the country has six to eight years to make needed 
reforms in the health care system if nothing is done people are 
going to rise up in protest he said 
medicaid a federalstate program that serves more than 26 
million poor americans is in worse shape than medicare 
rockefeller said eligibility differs from state to state and 
reimbursement rates are so low in some places that some physicians 
refuse to treat medicaid patients he said 
it is time to take the lessons we have learned over these 25 
years and put them to use in finally building a universal health 
system he said 
