shanghai chinas largest city with a population 
of more than 12 million will start fining couples who have a 
second child an amount equal to three times their annual income an 
official newspaper reported 
in most regions of china current fines are 10 percent of income 
stricter birth control regulations to take effect aug 1 will 
end secondchild privileges for farmers living in shanghais 
outskirts for oil workers and for brothers and children of 
revolutionary martyrs said the xinmin new peoples daily report 
which was seen in beijing today 
couples in second marriages will be allowed to have a second 
child only if they already have one child between them the paper 
said 
the report said that couples who have an illegal second child 
will be fined three times the total of their average annual income 
for the two years before the birth couples who have a third or 
more children without permission will be fined four to six times 
their annual income it said 
payment of the fines could be extended for only six years and 
at least 25 percent must be paid within the first year the report 
said 
in most regions of china current fines are 10 percent of income 
for up to 14 years after the birth of a second child 
the average wage in shanghai last year was 2500 yuan 530 
according to the municipal statistics bureau 
china adopted a onechild per couple policy in 1980 the rule is 
widely observed in crowded cities where women usually have jobs 
but is widely ignored in rural areas where families are willing to 
pay fines in order to have more children to help on their farms 
shanghai already has chinas lowest population growth rate 64 
per 1000 the national average is 142 the city says the stricter 
regulations are needed because current birth rates are exceeding 
previously set targets 
the government has acknowledged that its target of limiting 
population currently estimated at 11 billion to 12 billion in 
the year 2000 is not attainable 
estimates for the number of chinese at the turn of the century 
have climbed to 13 billion about 20 percent of the total world 
population 
