<TEXT>
the government today ordered a second 
teenage hijacker returned for trial in the soviet union saying 
sweden could not afford to be known as a haven for hijackers 
acting justice minister mona sahlin said soviet authorities have 
guaranteed that anatoly michajlenko 19 will be tried only for the 
hijacking the reason he was being extradited 
she said the soviets promised not to charge him with evading 
military service which is not an extraditable crime in sweden 
michajlenko was expected to be sent back within two weeks 
he was among five young men who hijacked soviet domestic 
airliners in june and early july three to sweden and two to 
finland all five asked to stay saying they were political 
dissidents or fugitives from the soviet army 
besides michajlenko sweden has extradited one hijacker and is 
considering the case of another finland has said it will extradite 
one hijacker and is reviewing the case of the second 
in ordering the extraditions swedish officials have said they 
believe democratic changes in the soviet union now make it possible 
for hijackers to receive a fair trial 
human rights groups soviet exiles and some ukrainian 
politicians asked that michajlenko be allowed to stay in sweden on 
humanitarian grounds 
ms sahlin said after a special cabinet meeting today that it 
was important that sweden not become a destination for hijackers 
she said the government will follow michajlenkos case and we 
believe these soviet guarantees are satisfactory to ensure that 
he is treated as sweden has asked 
