<TEXT>
the world health organization today raised its 
estimate of the number of people infected with the deadly aids 
virus to at least 8 million citing the diseases spread in asia 
and black africa 
the latest estimate of 8 to 10 million infections worldwide is 2 
million above the previous figure but within a range the agency has 
cited for some time 
particularly in asia the virus has been spreading much more 
quickly than expected who said 
the toll of hiv infection around the globe is worsening 
rapidly especially in developing countries dr michael merson 
head of whos antiaids program was quoted as saying in a 
statement issued by the agency hiv is the aids virus 
in summarizing regional developments the statement said the 
rate of new hiv infections generally was slowing in the developed 
world but merson warned against complacency since the spread is 
still quickening in some industrialized countries who didnt 
identify those countries 
the agency said that in subsaharan africa the estimate of 
hivinfected people had doubled to 5 million from 25 million in 
1987 due to the diseases spread in rural areas who said 1 in 40 
adult men and women are now believed to be virus carriers compared 
with 1 in 50 estimated earlier 
in asia the virus has spread rapidly among intravenous drug 
users and female prostitutes at least half a million asians are 
believed infected in an area where aids was virtually unknown two 
years ago 
who said the virus spread in asia latin america and 
subsaharan africa could force a dramatic upward revision of 
its prediction that 15 to 20 million infections will have occurred 
by the year 2000 
the un agency also said aids will kill at least 3 million 
women and children worldwide in the 1990s due to rising 
heterosexual transmission six times more than in the 1980s 
who has long said 5 to 10 million people worldwide are believed 
infected with hiv but has recently narrowed its estimates 
its previous figure issued last spring was 6 million to 8 
million 
the virus is transmitted through blood and other body fluids 
infection with the virus is different from developing aids 
itself which destroys the bodys immune system there is no known 
cure 
who lists more than 260000 reported aids cases worldwide but 
says the actual total is two to three times higher 
</TEXT>
