<TEXT>
scores of cattle and sheep farmers broke into a 
slaughterhouse and burned seven tons of imported german and irish 
meat to protest foreign competition police said today 
the incident occurred monday night in the maineetloire region 
of western france two days after farmers in the area poisoned 94 
sheep imported from britain 
police said a group of farmers stopped a meat truck monday 
morning that was empty of cargo but carried documents indicating 
meat had been delivered to a slaughterhouse in the town of 
fosseentigne 
in the evening about 100 men entered the slaughterhouse and set 
fire to seven tons of meat in a cold storage room police said no 
estimate of the damage was given 
the attack saturday occurred at a farm in deuxsevres where 206 
british sheep purchased by a french cooperative arrived friday for 
fattening before going to slaughter 
the farm owner joseph drouet heard noises in his sheep pens 
and found 94 of the animals dead police said they apparently had 
ingested an insecticide 
a caller claiming to represent local sheep farmers later 
telephoned media organizations to claim the attack in the name of 
deuxsevres herders 
sheep herders in the region have protested falling prices for 
months they blocked the route of the tour de france bicycle race 
july 2 and forced the riders to detour 
major farming organizations condemned the poisoning but said 
sheep herders were suffering from the loss of income 
its absolutely necessary to give them some hope said 
raymond lacombe president of the national federation of 
agriculture unions 
the government approved 113 million in aid last week to sheep 
herders to help them weather the poor market 
