<TEXT>
safety specialists had concerns about 
potential explosions in storage tanks at the hanford atomic weapons 
plant since the 1970s but authorities didnt acknowledge the 
problem until recently an internal investigation revealed today 
concern about possible explosions because of hydrogen 
accumulation in some of the atomic waste tanks at the weapons plant 
in eastern washington state surfaced last march when the energy 
department made the information public 
but a report by the departments office of nuclear safety 
concluded that a string of plant operators dating back 13 years 
were aware that flammable gas was being generated in the tanks and 
the significance was known as early as the late 1970s 
meanwhile a safety advisory panel to energy secretary james 
watkins suggested the department may not be taking the concern 
about the tanks seriously enough 
the technical basis for the analysis from which the hanford 
operator draws comfort about the safety of the tanks is weak 
considering the potential consequences of an accident the 
departments advisory committee on nuclear facility safety said in 
a letter to watkins 
the findings were released today by the senate government 
affairs committee at hearings into the safety concerns over the 
storage tanks at hanford and other weapons facilities 
sen john glenn dohio committee chairman said the panel 
wants to examine what threat the tanks pose to workers at the 
weapons plants and to nearby populations the committee has 
estimated a single tank could explode with the force of 36 tons of 
tnt and release significant radiation 
the hanford weapons facility has 177 nuclear waste storage tanks 
which contain highly radioactive byproducts from more than 40 years 
of plutonium production last march the energy department said 
some of the doublewalled tanks could explode because of a buildup 
of highly flammable hydrogen 
while acknowledging a problem the department repeatedly has 
said the likelihood is low of an explosion that would penetrate 
both walls of any of the tanks is low 
but in the letter to watkins john ahearne chairman of the 
advisory committee on nuclear facility safety suggested the 
potential for danger is underestimated 
the waste tanks are a serious problem the possibility of an 
explosion of an unstable chemical or a flammable gas must be taken 
seriously because of the amount of radioactive materials that 
could be released ahearne wrote 
top management of doe and the contractor is paying more 
attention to maximizing waste storage capacity and to minimizing 
potential leakage from the tanks than to achieving higher levels of 
tank safety he continued 
ahearne said there is an urgent need to determine what is in 
the tanks what are the risks and what actions should be taken to 
ameliorate the hazards the operators have only sketchy 
information on conditions ins the tanks 
in olympia wash meanwhile gov booth gardner said there 
appears to be no immediate danger to public health and safety 
from a cyanide compound that is in many of the tanks there had 
been concern last year that the compound may unleash a chemical 
reaction that would lead to an explosion 
concern about the cyanide issue prompted the later disclosure 
about the hydrogen buildup in the tanks since then the hydrogen 
problem has gained most of the focus and is considered the more 
troublesome 
