testimony in the federal court challenge to 
pennsylvanias restrictive abortion law today took aim at a 
provision requiring women to notify their husbands before getting 
abortions 
attorneys for a group of doctors and abortion clinics seeking to 
overturn key sections of the law tried to show that battered women 
would not take advantage of exemptions in the law from the 
notification requirement 
psychologist lenore walker testified that battered women are 
very reluctant to talk about physical or emotional abuse because 
that forces them to relive the painful experience 
as for the requirement that husbands be notified of abortions 
forcing a battered woman to notify her husband is like giving him 
a hammer to beat her she said 
under the law women would have to sign a statement for their 
doctor certifying that they had informed their husband or that 
they had not because they feared bodily harm if they did so 
because the husband was not the father because the pregnancy 
resulted from spousal rape or because the woman could not locate 
the husband after diligent effort 
the only exception for the requirement of a signed statement 
would be in the case of a medical emergency 
ms walker also criticized a section of the law that requires a 
24hour waiting period for an abortion ms walker said forcing an 
abused woman to wait 24 hours before obtaining an abortion would be 
detrimental 
the case which opened monday is being watched by activists on 
both sides of the abortion debate because of its potential to 
present a challenge to roe vs wade the 1973 ruling that 
established the right to an abortion 
the lawsuit argues that the abortion controls passed by the 
legislature in 1988 and 1989 infringe on the rights of women 
the measures require a woman to notify her husband before 
obtaining an abortion and wait 24 hours between visiting a clinic 
and receiving an abortion doctors must offer counseling to women 
seeking abortions and minors must get the consent of one parent or 
a court order to receive an abortion 
portions of the law have been blocked by the federal court 
pending a ruling on the lawsuit 
only guam a us territory in the pacific has adopted more 
stringent controls 
