president bush and british prime minister 
margaret thatcher will help celebrate the 40th anniversary of the 
aspen institute an organization designed to help global leaders 
focus on critical issues 
we wanted the strongest leaders we could get said david t 
mclaughlin president and chief executive officer of the institute 
its the first time two heads of state have come were 
absolutely delighted 
bush is scheduled to give the opening address thursday at the 
institute and thatcher who arrives wednesday will give the 
closing address on sunday 
the theme of this years symposium is renewal leadership and 
values for the 21st century 
the nonprofit institute is the brainchild of the late chicago 
businessman walter paepcke whose dream was to help refocus the 
worlds attention on the cultural contributions of germans at a 
time when its eyes were turned to the brutal horrors left by the 
nazi regime 
in 1950 he convinced humanist dr albert schweitzer to travel 
from his home in africa to aspen to help celebrate the 200th 
birthday of german poet and statesman wolfgang goethe that was the 
seed that launched the 11 millionayear institute 
the principle thrust of the institute then and very much 
today was to bring together leaders from the private sector to 
really discuss some of the critical issues of our time said 
mclaughlin the former dartmouth college president who has headed 
the institute since 1987 
when schweitzer arrived he found a near ghost town with 
mudpaved streets and little else to offer when bush and thatcher 
arrive this week they will find an upscale posh ski resort 
former west german chancellor willy brandt and supreme court 
justices are among the speakers who have addressed the institute 
nearly 1000 people will gather for this years symposium which 
will feature forums on the environment education eastern europe 
developing third world countries and national health care 
bush and thatcher are scheduled to meet thursday their fourth 
round of discussions in three months 
prior to her symposium address thatcher plans a whirlwind tour 
friday of the national center for atmospheric research in boulder 
and the strategic defense initiative national test facility and the 
north american aerospace defense command in colorado springs 
a number of current and former global executives will lead the 
symposium forums including paul volcker former federal reserve 
board chairman rita klimova ambassador of the czech and slovak 
federal republic robert s mcnamara former president of the world 
bank group and ernest l boyer president of the carnegie 
foundation for the advancement of teaching 
in the past 40 years the institute has grown from its base in 
aspen to include administrative headquarters at wye md and 
branches in germany france italy japan and the united kingdom 
