<TEXT>
federal safety investigators today criticized 
exxon corp for operating tankers with reduced crews who dont get 
sufficient rest they said that situation existed on the exxon 
valdez which spilled 11 million gallons of crude oil into alaskas 
prince williams sound 
the national transportation safety board was voting today on the 
causes of the nations worst oil spill 
its initial conclusions found that the captain of the vessel 
improperly handed over the helm to his third mate the board said 
the mates fatigue contributed to his inability to guide the vessel 
around ice 
the board found that similar conditions of deck officers with 
inadequate rest exist on other exxon tankers due to a company 
policy of operating with reduced crews 
it also criticized exxon incentive awards for crews who work 
long hours and said the oil company has manipulated shipboard 
reporting of overtime and workload 
the 340page report by the national transportation safety board 
staff was getting a final review by board members before it is to 
be made public in several weeks the board planned to vote on the 
probable cause of the march 24 1989 spill 
the panel considered a long list of conclusions and 
recommendations stemming from the disaster 
among the boards conclusions in the early discussion were 
the decision by the exxon valdez captain to leave his third 
mate in charge as the tanker was being maneuvered around a massive 
ice floe was improper and went against exxon policies and coast 
guard rules 
coast guard rules on staffing ships do not adquately consider 
the workload 
the coast guard has been unduly narrow in perspective in 
allowing exxon ships to operate with inadequate crew failing to 
consider the amount of work required in loading the ships before 
they go out to sea 
board chairman james kolstad said the accident was the costliest 
the board ever investigated he said cleanup costs had so far 
totalled 2 billion 
the investigation was aimed at greatly reducing the risk of 
similar accidents kolstad said 
with one vacancy on the fivemember ntsb the possibility of a 
deadlock loomed on some issues although reports normally are not 
brought to the final stage until members have had a chance to read 
them and discuss any disagreements with staff investigators 
the report covers drug and alcohol testing of the crew the 
exxon crews operation of the vessel coast guard traffic control 
standards for staffing tankers and coast guard facilities that 
guide them and government and private emergency response to the 
spill said board spokeswoman drucella andersen 
it does not however cover the cleanup operation which is an 
environmental matter she said 
ms andersen said the board received no formal complaint or 
allegation about the blood alcohol tests taken on joseph hazelwood 
the exxon valdezs captain more than 10 hours after his ship broke 
open 
hazelwoods lawyers claimed last week that tests purportedly 
showing that his blood had a 06 percent alcohol content were 
botched and were followed by a cover up that denied him a fair 
trial earlier this year in alaska the coast guard standard for 
drunkenness is 04 percent 
an alaska jury acquitted the captain of being intoxicated but 
convicted him on one misdemeanor charge of negligent discharge of 
oil a judge fined him 50000 and ordered him to spend 1000 hours 
cleaning alaskan beaches hazelwood has appealed the verdict 
last week the coast guard dismissed charges of drunkenness and 
misconduct against hazelwood but suspended his license as a ships 
master for nine months after he pleaded no contest to breaking 
coast guard rules 
the violations included drinking within four hours before taking 
command of the vessel and leaving the bridge to his first officer 
while the tanker was headed for jagged bligh reef where it split 
open 
safety board conclusions carry no legal force but are used as 
possible guidelines for congressional and other government action 
by law ntsb analyses and conclusions are not admissible as 
evidence in courts 
kolstad took charge of the investigation shortly after the spill 
and sent an eightmember team to look into various aspects of the 
accident and the futile attempts to stop the spread of the oil 
kolstad received some criticism from former board investigators 
for not going to the site himself he said he did not want to add 
to the list of highprofile transportation and environmental 
officials drawing attention there 
two months after the exxon valdez ran aground the ntsb held a 
weeklong public hearing in alaska interviewing 27 witnesses and 
collecting 115 exhibits 
the 987footlong ship has since been renamed the exxon 
mediterranean and has been undergoing tests for service on oil 
trade routes in the mediterranean sea or the middle east 
the transportation department congress and other agencies have 
looked into various aspects of the spill but the ntsb conducts the 
official inquiry into all accidents involving planes trains 
ships highways and pipelines 
