aflcio leaders wrestling with the abortion issue 
agreed today that the powerful labor federation should continue its 
decadelong path of neutrality on the divisive subject 
the executive council of the 142 millionmember organization 
voted not to take a position on abortion 
the overwhelming view of the council was that this was a 
matter of deep conscience conviction and religion on the part of 
union members aflcio president lane kirkland said 
kirkland said only two or three members of the 34member council 
dissented during todays voice vote he said the group did not 
think any stance taken by the union as a whole could change the 
minds of individual members 
three members of the council are women 
todays vote was to accept the recommendation of an 18member 
panel of aflcio union presidents who monday urged the full 
governing council not to take sides on abortion 
on monday one of the union leaders who had ben pushing a 
prochoice stand accused colleagues of dragging their feet on 
an issue crucial to luring more women and minorities into the 
struggling labor movement 
however the union leader who spoke on condition of anonymity 
