americans working with refugees expressed 
mixed reactions tuesday to congressional proposals to lend money to 
immigrants so they can establish themselves without going on 
welfare 
the author of one measure rep stephen solarz dny said his 
plan would establish a federal program of refugee loan guarantees 
to encourage private lenders to give loans to employable refugees 
solarz said at a house hearing on resettlement that his goal was 
to make optimum use of scarce refugee resettlement dollars so 
that more victims of persecution and oppression can come to the 
united states 
the solarz plan calls for qualifying refugees to receive an 
average loan of 7500 to be repaid over a decade even if the 
default rate were 30 percent solarz said that his estimates 
suggest that the refugee program might save as much as tens of 
millions of dollars per year 
another proposal from sen howard metzenbaum dohio would give 
some refugees interestfree loans to cover half the average cost of 
resettlement the refugees would be required to repay the loans 
nicolas dimarzio executive director of the us catholic 
conferences migration and refugee services said the group could 
not endorse private sponsorship proposals right now because it 
didnt know enough about them 
we are concerned that while both of these approaches seek to 
eventually reduce federal outlays for refugees neither ensures 
that these programs would result in an increase of refugee 
admissions to the united states he said 
moreover he said he could not be sure the proposals would be 
equitable 
gary rubin of the american jewish committee a group that 
promotes the rights of jews around the world refused to endorse 
the proposals and said more study is needed 
it will obviously be a very complex task to set up a workable 
program rubin said the proposed legislation does not yet 
take all of these factors into account 
private sponsorship initiatives are expected to allow about 
15000 refugees primarily those from the soviet union and cuba to 
find new lives in the united states this year 
