<TEXT>
motorists who clog californias 
freeways on wednesday begin paying the states biggest tax hike 
ever a voterapproved nickelagallon levy on fuel aimed at 
reducing the highway gridlock 
this nickel is adding insult on top of injury said dennis 
radabaugh a contra costa sheriffs deputy who lives in walnut 
creek he said the increase was one of several nickels thats 
obviously going to raise my whole cost of living 
the tax rises an additional cent jan 1 then one more penny 
each subsequent new years day through 1994 that will provide the 
majority of funding for an 18 billionplus 10year highway and 
masstransit rail construction program that voters approved june 5 
in the form of proposition 111 
altogether the average california motorist will soon be paying 
more than a cent per mile in excise and sales taxes 
road and rail construction has not kept pace with population 
because of inflation and political paralysis on the issue drivers 
waste more than 400000 hours a day because the average speed on 
urban freeways has fallen to about 20 mph during commuting hours 
in the next decade the number of licensed drivers is expected 
to rise 18 percent currently there are about 19 million registered 
drivers in california and some 25 million vehicles 
the new levies will double the current state excise tax per 
gallon of gas from 9 to 18 cents there already is a federal excise 
tax of 91 cents per gallon and a sales tax per 1 of 625 to 725 
cents depending on how much the county tacks on above the states 
basic 625 cents 
the state excise tax also will go up at the same rate on diesel 
aviation fuel for light airplanes and marine gasoline 
but drastic as that may seem to californians the states gas 
tax after the initial nickel hike will rank 37th among states and 
12th after the full increase goes into effect up from 47th said 
penny hill a spokeswoman for the road information program a 
washingtonbased nonprofit research organization 
state excise taxes on gas range from 223 cents per gallon in 
nebraska to 75 cents a gallon in georgia she said 
proposition 111 was supported by a bipartisan government 
business and labor coalition 
it was rejected by rural voters who believed they would benefit 
less than cities despite plans to distribute funds throughout the 
state 
but there was no organized opposition and the scattered critics 
for the most part see the tax as unfortunate but necessary 
service stations owners are not happy about the gas tax were 
usually opposed to any tax increase but we know this one was 
designated for transportation improvements said art boswell a 
spokesman for the california service station and automotive repair 
association 
state officials said they believe motorists will take the tax 
hike in stride everyone they said is used to fluctuations in gas 
prices which are also expected to rise because of increases in the 
cost of crude oil 
some service station attendants in san francisco los angeles 
san bernardino and sacramento said it was business as usual tuesday 
while others said sales were up to 25 percent brisker as people 
stocked up before the price went up a few stations said they ran 
out of gas early because of the increased business 
