<TEXT>
a computerized databank of actions taken 
against incompetent physicians and dentists will open its 
electronic doors sept 1 health and human services secretary louis 
sullivan said tuesday 
the national practitioner databank is intended to prevent 
physicians and dentists who have been disciplined from moving to 
another state and setting up new practices without detection he 
said 
the databank will store reports of malpractice actions 
licensure disciplinary actions by state medical and dental boards 
and actions by professional societies hospitals and other health 
care entities after a formal peer review process 
the reports must be made beginning sept 1 actions taken before 
then do not have to be reported 
hospitals will be required to check the databank when a 
physician or dentist applies to join the medical staff or receive 
clinical privileges sullivan said 
also hospitals will be required to check the databank every two 
years concerning physicians and dentists on their medical staffs or 
those who have clinical privileges 
state licensing boards also will have access to the information 
and individual physicians dentists and other health care 
professionals will be able to see their own records attorneys 
representing a physician or dentist may have access under limited 
conditions 
charges for use of the databank will be 2 per name for each 
request however individual practitioners will not be charged for 
seeing his or her own file 
the ralph naderfounded group public citizen has been critical 
of the data bank because members of the public will not have access 
to the information and retroactive reporting will not be required 
the public citizen health research group recently put out its 
own information in a book called the 6892 questionable doctors 
disciplined by states or the federal government it lists the 
names of physicians and dentists who have been disciplined 
</TEXT>
