<TEXT>
scattered rain lower temperatures and 
shorter days helped firefighters battle more than 100 blazes that 
have burned more than 2 million acres of alaskan wildlands a 
spokeswoman said tuesday 
smaller fires burned in washington idaho oregon and california 
several days of cloudy skies and temperatures in the 50s and 60s 
across much of alaskas interior have reduced the intensity of many 
fires said sue mitchell a spokeswoman for the interagency fire 
information center 
and were having darkness at night now which really helps 
cool things down she said 
earlier this summer the sun was almost continually above the 
horizon and temperatures in some places were in the 90s drying out 
forests and tundra 
alaskas wildfire season began on july 1 as lightning strikes 
ignited dozens of blazes in remote regions 
on tuesday more than 100 fires burned across the state 
more than 827 firefighters battled the tok river fire near the 
town of tok 175 miles southeast of fairbanks the blaze has charred 
about 91200 acres 
crews have nearly surrounded the 142squaremile fire with a 
fire line mitchell said using bulldozers and hand tools crews 
have removed vegetation along more than 60 miles of fire line 
hoping to rob the advancing fire of fuel 
the states largest fire burned across 275000 acres along 
either side of the coleen river on the southern flank of the brooks 
range inside the arctic national wildlife refuge 
