<DOCNO> AP900731-0134 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the justice department is reviewing the 
appeals court decision that upset oliver l norths irancontra 
convictions because of concern about its possible impact on future 
cases officials said tuesday 
in a 21 decision a panel of the us circuit court of appeals 
here ordered a witnessbywitness review of the evidence to 
determine if norths trial was influenced by congressional 
testimony he gave under a limited grant of immunity from 
prosecution 
the use immunity grant meant that the detailed descriptions 
of the irancontra affair that north gave congress couldnt be used 
against him as evidence in a criminal trial 
independent councsel lawrence e walshs office is considering 
whether to seek a rehearing of the case by the full 12member 
appellate court or to ask the supreme court to review the issue 
walsh has at least a month to decide 
justice department spokesman dan eramian said officials were 
concerned about the decisions impact on a limited number of cases 
where the government might want to prosecute someone whose 
congressional testimony received widespread publicity 
other department officials speaking on condition of anonymity 
said the new procedures could have wider implications particularly 
in cases where defendants receive limited immunity from courts or 
grand juries 
north a former national security council aide was convicted 
last year of three felonies including aiding and abetting the 
obstruction of congress and destruction of government documents 
gesell placed north on probation and ordered him to perform 1500 
hours of community service 
the appellate court held that us district judge gerhard a 
gesell should have conducted extensive hearings to determine if 
grand jurors witnesses and prosecutors were influenced by norths 
congressional testimony which was aired on network television 
gesell had held that the elaborate procedures that walsh imposed 
to shield grand jurors and his staff from the publicity prevented 
the case from being influenced by norths testimony 
walsh also placed under court seal evidence his investigation 
found before north appeared on capitol hill to prove that the case 
was derived independently from the congressional testimony 
as it stands the decision applies only to federal courts in the 
nations capital but those courts try many of the socalled 
political cases in which criminal defendants already have been 
subjects of congressional inquiries 
eramian said the department was conducting its own review of the 
july 20 decision 
he stressed that the justice department was not necessarily 
contemplating participation in any appeal under the independent 
counsel law the justice department could file a 
friendofthecourt brief to state its legal views on the case 
the appeals court panels majority set what federal prosecutors 
called a very high perhaps impossible standard for proving that 
evidence was not derived from testimony that a defendant gave under 
a limited immunity grant 
some legal experts say the north decision radically extends a 
1972 supreme court decision that bars prosecutors from introducing 
evidence that was derived in any way from testimony obtained as a 
result of limited immunity 
what they did in this case was to virtually change use 
immunity into transactional immunity under which the government 
agrees not to prosecute someone in return for their cooperation 
said g robert blakey a notre dame law professor who drafted the 
1970 use immunity statute 
the court in effect created a rule that once anything was 
disseminated as widely as norths testimony it necessarily 
affected the trial blakey said 
gerald caplan a george washington university law professor 
called the north decision sort of an ingenious way of overruling 
a supreme court decision from a group that would otherwise be 
thought to have a prosecution bias 
president reagan appointed the two circuit judges who joined in 
the ruling laurence h silberman and david sentelle president 
carter appointed patricia wald the appellate courts chief judge 
who dissented from the decision 
the two majority judges simply let north off blakey said 
this opinion harkens back to a kind of solicitude for the 
defendant that was characteristic of warren court opinions and 
hardly charactistic of reagan court opinions 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

