<TEXT>
campaign reforms approved by the senate 
envision new multimilliondollar public contributions to senate 
candidates at the same time taxpayers are cutting back donations to 
presidential campaigns 
the senate still debating the measure has approved provisions 
that include public financing of up to 20 million for broadcast 
time the money would be available to candidates who agree to stay 
within a spending limit 
also approved monday were other incentives to abide by the 
ceiling including postal discounts help in responding to 
interestgroup attacks and money to offset funds raised by an 
opponent who exceeds the spending limit 
the public money for the senate races would come from the 
existing and already strained fund for presidential campaigns 
taxpayers can choose to contribute to the fund by earmarking 1 
from their tax returns 
but contributions to the presidential campaign are dwindling 
the presidential fund is in trouble said fred eiland a 
spokesman for the federal election commission we have been 
saying since two years ago that there is a problem and that its 
going to be more serious and that congress needs to do something 
taxpayer participation in the presidential campaign fund reached 
an alltime high of 287 percent in 1980 and fell to a record low 
of 201 percent in 1988 the fec said 
donations to the fund dwindled from 336 million in 1987 to 
322 million in 1989 eiland said 
tax returns through may 1990 brought in about 25 million and 
the internal revenue service says relatively few returns are still 
expected from taxpayers given extensions 
the strain on the fund has been compounded by inflation as 
participation has dropped payouts to candidates have been rising 
each year to adjust for inflation 
the fec has advised the president congress and the treasury 
secretary that it expects a 202000 shortfall in 1992 when the 
presidential campaign is projected to cost about 184 million 
if no incumbent is seeking reelection in 1996 that could mean 
more candidates for both major parties the fec projects a 238 
million shortfall that year for an election expected to cost about 
270 million 
the fec paid out 178 million for the 1988 election as of may 
1990 there was a balance of 108 million in the presidential 
campaign fund 
