<TEXT>
a freighter left colombo for 
rebelheld jaffna on tuesday to evacuate about 100 foreign 
nationals caught in the cross fire between tamil guerrillas and the 
army 
officials meanwhile reported that at least 54 people were killed 
in two days of fighting across this island nation off the southeast 
tip of india 
military officials said the freighter lanka siri sailed for 
point pedro at the northernmost tip of the jaffna peninsula which 
has been severed from the mainland by the 50day fighting the ship 
was expected to return wednesday 
the officials speaking on condition of anonymity said 90 of 
those awaiting evacuation carried british passports most were 
tamil expatriates who were visiting their homeland when fighting 
broke out on june 11 ending a 13month ceasefire in the 
7yearold civil war 
one person carried a swiss passport officials said and they 
did not know the others nationalities 
communications with jaffna have been cut off 
the evacuation was being supervised by the international 
committee of the red cross said the officials 
military officials said at least seven rebels and five soldiers 
were killed in fighting tuesday in northwestern mannar 
on monday night unidentified gunmen killed 20 tamil civilians 
in northeastern kantalai village military officials and residents 
said 
tamil residents of nearby trincomalee town blamed the and said 
the killings were in retribution for a tamil rebel ambush on troops 
two days earlier 
military officials said the assailants were moslems who attacked 
to avenge tamil raids on their community 
the officials said earlier tuesday that rebels shot 14 moslems 
to death in the ampara district south of trincomalee 
moslems who comprise about 7 percent of the 16 million 
population are often caught in the middle of the civil war between 
the minority tamils and sinhalesedominated government the rebels 
accuse them of siding with the army 
in jaffna at least six rebels and two police were killed 
military officials said they said guards at palali airfield killed 
the rebels and that the police were killed when air force planes 
accidentally dropped bombs close to jaffna fort 
the deaths raise to more than 3000 the number of combatants 
killed in the fighting the latest phase of the war for an 
independent tamil homeland many civilians also have died 
tamils makie up 18 percent of the million population they 
complain they are discriminated against in jobs and education by 
the sinhalese who make up 75 percent of sri lankans and who 
control the army and the government 
more than 14000 people have died in the tamil revolt since it 
began in 1983 
