<TEXT>
under the pressure of a lawsuit filed by four 
major newspapers the national endowment for the arts reversed 
itself tuesday and announced that a meeting of its advisory council 
to review controversial grant decisions will be open to the public 
chairman john e frohnmayer abandoned plans for a news blackout 
of the council sessions later this week after the los angeles 
times the new york times the washington post and the philadelphia 
inquirer sued the nea in us district court on monday 
it is highly unusual for any agency of the federal government 
to conduct application review in the glare of public scrutiny 
frohnmayer said in a statement but i am convinced that there are 
significant advantages to having our citizens aware of how this 
small amount of their money is invested in cultural activities all 
americans enjoy as a result of the endowment 
the nea is an independent federal agency with a budget of 171 
million most of which supports a wide variety of artists and arts 
institutions with federal grants that must be matched by private 
funds 
the 26member national council on the arts the endowments 
presidentially appointed advisory body plans to begin a threeday 
meeting here friday in the past its meetings have been open to 
the public except for sessions devoted to reviewing grant 
applications recommended by the neas panels of outside arts 
experts on theater dance music and other disciplines 
as late as monday frohnmayer had insisted that the councils 
grantreview sessions would be closed but on tuesday he said he 
decided to lift the news blackout partly because a majority of 
council members had voted at their last meeting in may to open the 
sessions 
in their lawsuit seeking a temporary restraining order against 
the nea the four newspapers said a news blackout would prevent the 
public from observing the council as it reconsiders frohnmayers 
veto of panelapproved grants to four controversial avantgarde 
theater performers in late june 
after frohnmayers announcement the newspapers lawyers 
withdrew the lawsuit 
one of the lawyers patrick j carome had said earlier that the 
nea was acting as if theyre giving away private money when in 
fact its taxpayer dollars arts supporters said the public is 
entitled to know how its tax money is being spent 
at the council meetings this weekend frohnmayer also was 
expected to ask the council to reconsider its recommendation that 
he reject two grants to the institute of contemporary art in 
philadelphia he said the councils discussion of the grants in may 
was inadequate and its information was incomplete 
it was the same philadelphia institute that started the current 
nea controversy when it used endowment funds to organize a 
traveling exhibition of sexually explicit works by the late 
photographer robert mapplethorpe 
last fall at the urging of sen jesse helms rnc and other 
nea critics congress voted to prohibit federal support for any 
artistic works that may be considered obscene and include 
depiction of sex acts sadomasochism homoeroticism or sexual 
exploitation of children 
frohnmayer told an independent commission created by congress to 
study the neas grantmaking procedures that he still opposes 
legislation to restrict the content of federally supported art 
but the endowments chairman said he believes that an arts 
project that is so offensive that it simply leads to 
confrontation and solidification of positions should not receive 
government support 
frohnmayer has issued guidelines to nea grant applicants to 
refrain from using federal funds to create works that might violate 
the supreme courts 1973 obscenity standards he told the 
commission monday that he could accept a law imposing penalties on 
nea grant recipients who are convicted on obscenity charges 
