<TEXT>
debris found on the ocean floor 90 miles south 
of here probably fell from a united airlines jumbo jet that ripped 
open last year the leader of the deepsea search said tuesday 
i would say its a very good chance better than 50 percent 
its the debris field from the jet said bob whaley leader of 
the search 
the largest piece of debris a metal object about 10 feet long 
is roughly the size of the 10by10foot cargo door that tore away 
from the boeing 747 along with a chunk of fuselage sweeping nine 
passengers to their deaths whaley said 
the national transportation safety board asked the navy to find 
the cargo door in hopes an examination of it would help the agency 
write better aviation safety rules 
its up to the ntsb to decide if there should be an attempt to 
retrieve the debris the agency hadnt made a decision by late 
tuesday said lt cmdr bob anderson a navy spokesman 
whaley said several factors make him think the debis is from 
united flight 811 
the debris was found in an area where navy radar tracked the 
door falling into the ocean 
the bottom nearly 15000 feet down is flat and silty older 
objects on the ocean floor probably would have sunk into the silt 
the largest piece roughly matches the size of the cargo door 
the debris field about three miles long runs north to south 
the direction the plane was traveling 
searchers aboard a 224foot navy tug used a small 
remotecontrolled deepsea submarine to find the debris 
the subs sonar located the debris but searchers were unable to 
get a picture with the subs video camera to help confirm whether 
the debris is from the jet 
the jumbo jet carried 355 passengers when it left honolulu for 
new zealand on feb 24 1989 
shortly after takeoff a cargo door opened at 22000 feet 
tearing away a section of fuselage nine people were swept to their 
deaths and five others suffered serious injuries the crew managed 
to return the jet to honolulu 
the ntsb inquiry determined that faulty design of the locking 
mechanism probably caused a cockpit light to falsely indicate the 
door was locked 
the agency blamed united boeing co and the federal aviation 
administration for failing to correct problems with the door 
the search which began a week ago covered a 24squaremile 
section of ocean floor 
