proposals to reduce the role of political parties and 
specialinterest money in elections to the upper house of 
parliament officials said 
the recommendations offered by the electoral review committee 
mark a step toward political reform in japan following scandals 
that caused two prime ministers to resign last year the committee 
was set up in june 1989 to lessen the power of money in japanese 
politics 
the government plans to draw up legislation based on the 
proposals but opposition is strong and analysts believe it 
unlikely the government will adopt the proposals without change 
the report recommended keeping the mixed system of national and 
regional constituencies used in selecting the 252 delegates to the 
upper house but suggested voters be allowed to choose candidates 
by name when voting in the national constituencies 
that would decrease the role of parties and increase the 
importance of policy in campaigning the council argued critics of 
japans political system frequently cite lack of substantive policy 
debate during electioneering 
the report suggested the government provide more money for 
candidates to lessen their dependence on outside financing 
it recommended toughening election laws and requiring stricter 
reporting on the use of political funds 
kaifu pledged political reform to restore the prestige of his 
liberal democratic party and trust in the government he became 
prime minister last august after his two predecessors resigned in 
quick succession over money and sex scandals 
earlier proposals from the committee constituted a plan to 
reshape the more powerful lower house the panel suggested 
reformulating japans system of multipleseat constitutencies to 
bring greater equality to reduce politicians ability to raise 
money on their own and to tighten rules on reporting political 
donations 
