<TEXT>
the us environmental protection agency 
issued a wideranging smogcutting plan tuesday that includes a 
proposal to ban driving on some days in the region with the 
nations dirtiest air 
the courtordered plan is aimed at cutting ozone in los angeles 
to 14 percent of current levels by early next century and is a 
backup to one approved in 1989 by the south coast air quality 
management district ozone is a major component of smog 
the plan stemmed from an environmentalist lawsuit filed against 
1982 district air quality standards guidelines that current 
officials of the regional agency call timid they were superseded 
by stronger local rules last year 
the districts current threeyear plan affects everything from 
lawnmowers to petroleum refineries at an estimated cost of 262 
billion a year 
later steps of that plan include the use of technology not yet 
developed making its effectiveness a guessing game 
the district covers orange county and parts of los angeles san 
bernardino and riverside counties an area where more than 12 
million people live in the worst air pollution in the country in 
1988 the most recent year available los angeles exceeded the 
national standard for ozone 150 times compared with 20 times for 
new york and chicago 
the most stringent sections of the epa plan which doesnt 
become final until next year wont go into effect until after 
1995 the entire plan would take effect only if state and regional 
governments fail to significantly reduce smog 
state and local authorities have been engaged in an 
extraordinary effort to address this problem themselves which we 
all hope will render a federal plan as unnecessary epa western 
regional administrative director daniel w mcgovern told a downtown 
news conference 
environmentalists who brought the lawsuit characterized the epa 
plan as insurance to make the district deliver 
we have been very concerned that the local district has been 
backsliding said coalition for clean air president jan 
chattenbrown whose organization was a plaintiff with the sierra 
club this plan will send a clear message if the district 
wont do the job the epa will step in 
the epa guidelines include a reluctant proposal for nodrive 
days to reduce carbon monoxide under such a plan motorists with 
odd numbers on their license plates would be permitted to drive 
every other day and those with even tag numbers on another 
the nodrive days would be enforced from november through 
february and would force affected commuters to find some other way 
to work either through car pools or mass transit 
it is in the spirit of presenting all possibilities that we 
are presenting the nodrive day it is not one we are 
endorsing said mcgovern 
the nodrive plan could be used by the year 2000 if other 
methods fail 
the federal plan takes longer to achieve goals set by the 
regional agency the district plan calls for reducing current ozone 
averages by 86 percent in 2007 the epa by 2010 
it is our hope and expectation that the state plan will 
achieve its goals well in advance of the federal plan mcgovern 
said 
the epa will not use its proposed backup system until 1996 at 
the earliest because of confidence in current efforts said david 
howekamp chief of air and toxics for the agency 
he said the agency will be measuring pollution levels to 
determine whether the epa should begin enforcing its proposed 
regulations 
some features of the epa backup plan include 
mandatory reduction of emissions by 6 percent a year from 
pollution sources such as consumer products industrial and 
commercial solvents pesticides commercial food preparation and 
architectural coatings such as paint 
extending pollution control standards to construction 
equipment pleasure boats and offroad vehicles 
an ultra clean motor vehicle program that would require 
all new motor vehicles meet emissions limits 85 percent to 90 
percent cleaner than those for vehicles now sold 
</TEXT>
