million in federal funds to develop drugs that attack the 
infections killing people with aids government officials announced 
tuesday 
the national institute of allergy and infectious diseases is 
setting up a program that will provide a formal way for basic 
research scientists to collaborate with drug companies to design 
new drugs they said 
the urgency of the aids epidemic demands innovation anthony 
fauci director of the institute said in announcing the program 
a version of this program is already being used to bring 
together scientists of diverse backgrounds to work on drugs that 
attack the human immunodeficiency virus or hiv which causes aids 
three drugs discovered through the program are now being tested in 
clinical trials and others are in the pipeline he said 
aids activists have been strongly critical of federal scientific 
research on aids because they say too much attention has been 
focused on antiviral drugs to attack hiv and not enough on drugs 
to prevent and treat opportunistic infections 
in its announcement of the new research the institute said that 
the research program for antivirals did not preclude research on 
opportunistic infections but few applications for research in this 
area were received 
as a result the institute last year issued a request for 
applications specifically addressing opportunistic infections the 
institute said 
opportunistic infections some rare some ordinary often 
attack aids patients whose immune systems have been weakened by the 
disease causing 90 percent of aidsrelated deaths 
the most common infection is pneumosystis carinii pneumonia 
which occurs in about 85 percent of aids patients 
