<TEXT>
cervical cancer tests done every three years 
instead of every year are a lot less expensive and the overall 
accuracy is nearly the same a researcher says but others strongly 
disagree 
previous studies show that tests every three years on women aged 
20 to 65 are about 96 percent as effective at detecting cancerous 
or other abnormal cells as annual exams according to dr david m 
eddy of duke university 
in addition the threeyear exams offer a twothirds reduction 
in cost risk and inconvenience according to eddys article in 
wednesdays edition of the journal annals of internal medicine 
but women at high risk for cervical cancer including those who 
smoke use oral contraceptives or have multiple sex partners may 
prefer exams every one to two years said eddy who reviewed 
studies on test frequency 
other researchers cautioned against following a recommendation 
based on cost and said physicians must consider human factors when 
deciding how often to examine their patients for cervical cancer 
the question is where to draw the line eddy said 
ideally this should be decided by women themselves 
while some researchers believe that women tested every three 
years will be more likely to forget the exam any interval from one 
to four years will deliver virtually the same benefits 
according to eddy 
however dr george malkasian the immediate past president of 
the american college of obstetricians and gynecologists warned that 
the death rate from cervical cancer would probably increase if 
eddys recommendation were followed 
cervical cancer strikes more than 13000 american women a year 
and causes about 7000 deaths annually if the cancer is caught in 
the early stages the survival rate after five years is about 90 
percent aid malkasian a senior consultant at the mayo clinic 
said in a telephone interview 
the most common test for cervical cancer is the pap test which 
detects abnormal or cancerous cells in the cervix the opening to 
the womb the test costs an average 76 per patient 
other cancer specialists argued that other factors should play a 
role in a womans decision regarding pap tests they point out that 
the test is one of the main reasons the number of deaths from 
cervical cancer has dropped 70 percent since it was first widely 
used in the 1940s 
many medical organizations including the obstetricians and 
gynecologists college and the american cancer society recommend 
that women who are at least 18 years old or sexually active have 
pap tests annually for three years after three negative tests 
women can reduce the frequency of the tests on their physicians 
advice the groups suggest 
some cancer specialists including dr robert young president 
of philadelphias fox chase cancer center believe that as more 
women rely on their gynecologist as their only provider of health 
care annual pap tests can supply the only contact between patient 
and physician 
despite eddys contention that only anecdotal evidence suggests 
that physicians are more likely to discover other medical problems 
in women who have annual pap tests there are certain realities 
that get lost in a cost analysis young said in a telephone 
interview 
he said he feared recommendations regarding pap tests based only 
on costeffectiveness would discourage some women from being 
examined at all of the 7000 women who die each year of cervical 
cancer 85 percent never had a pap test prior to the diagnosis 
according to young 
we need to encourage the wider use of pap smears he said 
but the american college of physicians which publishes the 
annals supports eddys recommendation of testing every three years 
all women should be given information on the expected 
benefits risks and costs and be allowed to choose the screening 
strategy that reflects their preferences according to the 
association 
