<TEXT>
bong jae jang rises before dawn and goes to the 
brooklyn terminal market where he stocks up on green plantain 
haitian mangos and other fruits and vegetables popular with the 
caribbean immigrants who used to shop at his store on church avenue 
in flatbush 
these days jangs trip is an academic exercise he knows most 
of the produce will sit unsold on the shelf rot in the july heat 
and wind up in the trash bin outside 
whos going to buy this he asks holding up a 
cellophanewrapped hunk of a vegetable called pium kim that is 
besieged by a swarm of tiny flies 
after six months a blackled boycott of jangs greengrocery 
continues even though the television cameras are gone and the 
pickets who gather outside the front door each afternoon have 
dwindled to a handful 
the boycotters avowed aim is to force the store to close 
jangs troubles began jan 18 when giselaine felissaint a 
haitian immigrant got into an argument with several of his 
employees over some merchandise one of them touched her she says 
the man knocked her down another employee says the man put his 
hands on her and she laid down 
five months passed before the stores manager pong ok jang was 
charged with assault but the incident immediately became a symbol 
of the tensions between the citys black and korean communities 
within a few months hundreds of demonstrators were gathering 
outside the store each day along with almost as many police and 
journalists pickets yelled racial slurs at the koreans and urged 
them to go back to where you came from 
tensions were heightened by the trial of some white youths 
accused of killing a black youth in the bensonhurst section in a 
special televised speech to the city mayor david dinkins pleaded 
for calm and understanding 
the problem runs far beyond a simple assault charge many blacks 
resent the way they are treated in some of the korean grocery 
stores that have opened in their communities and some are jealous 
of the immigrants business success the selfemployed account for 
67 percent of all city workers but only 34 percent of all black 
workers 
skeptics derided the boycott as a news media creation that would 
end as soon as the last camera crew departed they were wrong by 5 
pm there usually are about a dozen demonstrators behind the blue 
police barricades that line the sidewalk outside the store few 
neighborhood residents defy their cries of boycott and venture 
inside or visit another korean grocery across the street 
the stores have become a symbol of what has happened across 
this city in terms of the lack of recognizing the humanity of black 
people says george dames a spokesman for the flatbush coalition 
for economic empowerment a boycott group it was not an isolated 
incident 
since may however tensions there have been lessening if not 
dramatically then incrementally says lonnie soury spokesman 
for the citys human rights commission 
the rev roy thompson of st pauls episcopal church agrees i 
can drive by the store without getting stuck in traffic for a 
halfhour 
dinkins has appointed a factfinding panel and called for an end 
to the boycott but none seems likely soon there still have been 
no direct negotiations between the korean and haitian communities 
let alone jang and mrs felissaint she has refused to denounce the 
boycott and has filed a 6 million suit against the store 
people say end it but we cant just wave a magic wand 
says soury of the human rights commission which is trying to get 
talks started 
were trying to identify leaders who represent those with 
legitimate interests there are people who dont have an interest 
in settling the issue he says we think that if we can get a 
group of people who can meet we can make progress but theyre not 
meeting now 
according to a poll taken last month only 13 percent of new 
yorkers supported the boycott while 58 percent supported the 
koreans among blacks only 27 percent sympathized with the 
boycotters while 37 percent sided with the koreans boycott 
leaders say the results simply reflected biased news coverage 
jang 35 says he came here in 1983 and worked for five years at 
another store before opening his own before the boycott he says 
he routinely worked 17 hours a day and was robbed three times he 
shows off the scar where a robbers bullet entered his abdomen last 
year 
his business is being sustained largely by 5000 to 7000 a 
month in donations from the citys other korean grocers they 
will support him until the boycott is over says michael kang of 
the korean produce association he is their maginot line they 
think theyre going to be next 
jang is infuriated by the refusal of the police department to 
enforce a judges order that the protesters be kept 50 feet from 
his door the city has appealed arguing that the police should be 
allowed to use discretion in deciding where the protesters should 
stand 
jang says neither dinkins nor police commissioner lee brown 
wants to stand up to the boycotters and pass responsibility for 
dealing with them back and forth he does not speak english very 
clearly but he gets his point across they play a pingpong 
game they killing my dream 
to soury the boycott is a tragedy two immigrant groups are 
pitted against each other he says when they should be 
fighting together to demand more government aid for small 
businesses for blacks and koreans and everyone else 
