<TEXT>
stock prices may have risen to record highs this 
year but the game isnt getting any easier for small investors 
trying to figure out how to play the bull market without getting 
gored 
what are they to make of an environment where the dow jones 
industrial average can fall 100 points in about an hours time as 
it did on the morning of monday july 23 
or how can anyone invest conservatively when supposedly stable 
blue chips like american telephone amp telegraph mcdonalds and dow 
chemical may suddenly nosedive as they have done in recent weeks 
on even a mildly disappointing earnings report for a single 
threemonth period 
it is hard to recall another time when one poor quarter no 
matter what the reason could wipe out 20 to 25 percent of a 
stocks value said jay donnaruma an analyst at first albany 
corp in albany ny 
it is downright scary and that type of volatility will just 
keep even more people away 
amid all this seemingly chaotic activity financial advisers see 
some object lessons for what individual investors can and cannot 
reasonably hope to achieve in stocks and stockrelated investors 
in the blue monday market drop last week for example 
william brennan a specialist in financial planning at the big 
accounting firm of ernst amp young saw a clear message for small 
investors 
that kind of volatility indicates that they shouldnt be in 
the market on a shortterm basis brennan said 
the prudent investor has to make a longterm commitment to 
me longterm means for the foreseeable future unless there is 
some dramatic change in their own circumstances 
to further minimize the effects of shortterm market 
fluctuations brennan argues for a plan of regular periodic 
purchases rather than attempting to buy at bargain prices 
such a strategy he said gives investors the benefit of a 
system called dollarcostaveraging since over time fixed amounts 
of their money will buy more shares whenever prices are low 
even if they have expertise most small investors simply lack 
the necessary time and tools to trade stocks shortterm analysts 
say furthermore frequent trading usually incurs heavy transaction 
costs and taxes that increase the odds against success 
a longterm investment by contrast avoids most of those 
pitfalls while giving investors a chance to participate in the 
growth of the general economy and specific businesses 
greg smith an analyst at the investment firm of 
prudentialbache securities says he believes individual investors 
today are investing avidly in stocks especially through mutual 
funds seeking to keep up with inflation in such important areas of 
the economy as health care 
more and more people perceive that inflation is a staple with 
us particularly in the service sector smith observed they 
know that as they age they will have to buy services particularly 
health care services 
stocks he added have about as good a track record as an 
inflation fighter as anything else and they tend to be more liquid 
than alternative real assets such as real estate and collectibles 
while investing for the long term averts or minimizes some 
significant risks it is by no means a sure thing 
people who opt to own individual stocks might be smart or lucky 
enough to pick a company like philip morris which increased about 
tenfold in value from the late 1970s to the late 1980s while 
paying dividends that increased every year 
or they could wind up with a stock like lomas financial corp a 
major firm in the mortgage banking business which sold for more 
than 22 a share as recently as 1988 and last week traded for less 
than 50 cents 
for a haven from such misadventure many investors these days 
turn to professional managers running diversified portfolios of 
investments such as mutual funds 
in search of still more stability and certainty of course many 
individuals steer clear of stocks in favor of interestbearing 
investments with stated values that dont fluctuate for instance 
bank certificates of deposit and moneymarket mutual funds 
but the key problem with this sort of perceived safety brennan 
says is that youre always losing money to inflation 
</TEXT>
