<TEXT>
after decades of trying to top unrealistic 
production quotas china appears to be setting its sights on an 
economic restructuring similar to soviet perestroika 
the economic plans still aim at the lofty goal of quadrupling 
chinas 1980 gross national product by the year 2000 
but they are also intended to cure major impediments to economic 
growth including energy and transportation shortages and poor 
management that have left almost onethird of the nations 
industrial capacity idle 
minister of the state planning commission zou jiahua told a 
national conference on industrial production sunday the government 
is adjusting the economy to stop unnecessary production and to 
stimulate markets that were stifled during the inflationcurbing 
economic retrenchment that began in 1988 
chinas economy for the time being is not a question of 
production speed but the speed of the operation of the national 
economy as a whole the official xinhua news agency quoted zou as 
saying 
in addition to recent cuts in interest rates to stimulate 
investment the government has raised the states purchasing price 
for coal and allocated 1 billion for modernizing industries zou 
noted 
to stimulate demand for oversupplied items he said the state 
monopolys control over institutional purchases of office equipment 
and furniture color television sets refrigerators and hotel 
furbishings would be relaxed 
both china and the soviet union are struggling with major 
structural adjustments but chinas markets are full of goods 
unlike in the soviet union where stores are bare 
the russian term perestroika refers to the economic and 
social restructuring of society to make it run more efficiently 
the failure to revive the chinese industrial economy despite 
1988s austerity measures has raised fears of a recession 
according to one official estimate 34 percent of all chinese 
firms are in the red a figure that climbs to more than 50 percent 
in many areas shanghais industrial output edged up only 08 
percent from january to june while production in most interior 
provinces actually fell 
an infusion of 42 billion in loans for slumping industries 
from january to march double the amount for the same period in 
1989 led mainly to further overstocking of unsold products 
many chinese economists say fundamental structural problems 
namely poor quality and inefficiency resulting from inept 
management are hindering the economic recovery 
this country cannot afford to keep industry going by issuing 
endless loans feng ronger a director in the peoples bank of 
china told the englishlanguage china daily 
it is high time to change the countrys industrial structure 
and product mix ms feng was quoted as saying 
premier li peng and communist party general secretary jiang 
zemin have also urged structural reforms 
the market sluggishness that has appeared is not allround 
sluggishness it is structural sluggishness mainly due to 
the serious impropriety of our industrial structure resulting from 
many years of old practices the poor quality of enterprises and 
the poor quality or nonmarketability of some products li said 
in an economic report earlier this month 
li said banks should increase loans earmarked for upgrading 
enterprises and their equipment improving energy conservation and 
developing new products 
some economists have suggested that china adopt a shareholding 
system for its stateowned enterprises becoming a major 
stockholder in firms that raise their own capital and engage in 
profitsharing 
but the sheer size of chinas economic problems coupled with 
the potential for political unrest raises doubts as to just how 
much efficiencyoriented planners will be able to achieve 
</TEXT>
