blinder robinson amp co once the largest 
pennystock brokerage in the world has filed for protection from 
its creditors while it reorganizes under chapter 11 of the federal 
bankruptcy laws 
blinder robinson said in a statement issued monday that it has 
ceased to do business as a brokerage it said it intends to 
transfer its 250000 customer accounts and brokerage operations to 
another unidentified brokerage firm 
founder and president meyer blinder was not immediately 
available for comment 
robert davenport head of the security and exchange commissions 
regional office in denver said the sec has been aware of blinder 
robinsons teetering finances in recent weeks but did not know of 
the bankruptcy until monday night 
once the largest pennystock firm in the world blinder 
robinson had shrunk to onethird its former size amid 
investigations by federal regulators and investor lawsuits it 
recorded a loss of 148 million in 1988 and 117 million in 1989 
penny stocks are low cost high risk securities usually trading 
for less than 3 per share they are not listed on stock exchanges 
and typically are used to raise capital for new or small companies 
according to a filing made monday with the sec blinder 
robinson owed its customers 48 million in cash and other 
brokerage firms 400000 the brokerage also owed customers and 
other brokerage firms 70 million in securities the filing said 
blinder robinson was the target of numerous state and federal 
investigations blinder himself faces charges of racketeering and 
wire fraud in indictments handed down earlier this year by a grand 
jury in nevada 
although the government lawsuits cost blinder robinson millions 
in legal fees over the past decade a civil lawsuit won by onetime 
denver stockbroker donald walford may have been the last straw 
walford won a judgment worth about 57 million earlier this 
month when the colorado supreme court refused to hear any more 
appeals from blinder robinson that judgment which has not been 
fully paid by the firm had prompted meyer blinder to threaten 
bankruptcy in recent weeks 
in a state supreme court filing last week walfords attorney 
steve miller told the court blinder had threatened bankruptcy and 
had told him you took me out even though the sec couldnt for 
years you can tell that to the press 
miller said monday the bankruptcy might mean part of the 57 
million judgment never will be paid but he added it also means 
my civil lawsuit has closed the doors to blinder robinson 
blinder who in 1987 paid himself 94 million while the 
brokerage brought in about 138 million in revenues has taken a 
battering this year from government regulators as well 
on july 13 the sec filed a 24 million lawsuit against the 
selfproclaimed king of the penny stocks just three days after he 
lost the supreme court appeal to the walford lawsuit on april 27 
the sec ordered blinder out of the brokerage business and his firm 
to be shut for 45 days the order was stayed however pending 
appeals 
in the most critical blow delivered by the government a federal 
grand jury in las vegas nev handed down an 11count criminal 
indictment in february the indictment charged blinder and four 
other men with racketeering securities fraud and conspiracy to 
violate racketeering laws 
in november 1988 internal revenue service agents along with 
the sec staged a fourday raid at the blinder building looking for 
evidence of money laundering and stock fraud the evidence from 
that raid served in the grand jury investigation 
