<TEXT>
the trade ministry said tuesday the nation should 
begin sharing its technical prowess with the rest of the world 
partly to help ease foreign trade friction 
an advisory report released by the ministry of international 
trade and industry said japan should sell more technology overseas 
and should welcome increased numbers of foreign researchers at 
government and private institutes 
it said japanese companies voracious appetite for new 
technology causes the country to import more foreign technology 
than it exports in the form of patent royalties and proprietary 
rights despite its growing technological prowess 
its time to look to see what are the root causes of trade 
irritation and as a country which now produces 15 percent of the 
worlds gross national product to cope with them as quickly as 
possible said hidetoshi nishimura director of the ministrys 
machinery and information industries bureau 
after attaining economic growth on the basis of technology 
imported from the west it is time for japan to export its 
technology to the rest of the world he said 
he said the ministry would try to encourage transfers of 
technology by creating favorable conditions including tax 
credits in a program being formulated 
private companies pay for about 80 percent of japans research 
and development compared with less than 50 percent in the united 
states and carefully guard their technology from rival businesses 
this has led to questions about whether they would be willing to 
share their most advanced technology with foreign interests 
last year japanese companies were the top four recipients of 
patents in the united states and reportedly filed nearly half the 
patents in the world 
in the 1960s and 1970s before the development of extensive 
private japanese research capabilities the trade ministry played 
an important role in guiding japanese research efforts for 
developing key technologies in areas such as computers and 
semiconductors 
but as trade friction has intensified in recent years 
especially with the united states the ministry has begun pursuing 
a reversal of its exportfirst orientation 
the report said japan bought 439 million more technology from 
overseas in 1988 than it sold while the united states sold 73 
billion more than it acquired 
the ratio of japanese technology exports to imports has 
increased but remains at a deficit nishimura said 
about 87000 japanese researchers were working aboard in other 
industrialized nations during 1988 while only about 9000 
researchers from those countries were in japan the report said 
nishimura said the growing costs of research in basic science 
also have increased the need for international cooperative research 
programs and for japan as a wealthy country to take a stronger 
role 
in the past western nations took a leading role in the 
exchange of research now is the time for japan to do so he said 
the ministry is preparing budget requests for implementation of 
the report which was prepared by a committee of academics and 
officials from companies such as sony hitachi and toyota 
nishimura said 
</TEXT>
