chrysler corps secondquarter earnings dropped 
472 percent compared with last year as incentives absorbed a huge 
chunk of profits the automaker said tuesday 
the results when combined with earnings reported last thursday 
by general motors corp and ford motor co showed profits for the 
big three tumbled 422 percent in the apriljune quarter this year 
compared with the same period last year 
the figures were generally in line with what wall street 
analysts had predicted chryslers stock closed unchanged at 
1512 a share 
chrysler like gm and ford blamed incentive costs during the 
quarter for dragging down earnings the effects of the incentives 
were more noticeable at chrysler than at ford or gm 
if not for the huge yeartoyear increase in perunit 
incentive costs chairman lee iacocca said we would have made 
more money this quarter than we did in the second quarter of 1989 
iacocca and analysts said the companys costcutting program 
designed to carve 15 billion out of 26 billion in annual costs 
by the end of this year contributed to the companys profits 
chrysler said it earned 180 million or 81 cents a share 
during the quarter this year compared with 341 million or 146 
a share during the same period last year 
revenues fell to 88 billion from 99 billion 
chrysler declined to say precisely what its incentive costs 
were but spokesman tom houston said they were more than 1000 per 
vehicle during the second quarter 
auto analyst douglas laughlin of bear stearns amp co of new york 
estimated that chrysler spent about 1400 on incentives per 
vehicle thats up sharply from his estimate of about 800 per 
vehicle during the same period last year 
analysts have said and chrysler has acknowledged that the 
company may show a loss in the third quarter as it stops production 
at its two minivan plants for retooling for the 1991 model year 
minivans are among chryslers most profitable products 
laughlin said chrysler will increase its cost savings by putting 
more efficient manufacturing methods into operation for the 91 
models 
ford vice president and treasurer david mccammon said last week 
that his company spent about 1050 on incentives for each car and 
truck sold during the period gm like chrysler declines to say 
how much it spends on incentives 
ford said it made 7707 million in the second quarter down 45 
percent from last year while gm reported secondquarter earnings 
fell 40 percent to 9001 million 
gm and ford also blamed economic instability in brazil for 
cutting their profits and ford added that lingering effects of 
strikes in the united kingdom and belgium further dented earnings 
the auto industry has been in a slump since the fourth quarter 
of last year when vehicle sales took a dive and inventories of 
unsold vehicles rose sharply 
to get rid of the inventory automakers boosted their incentive 
programs during the first quarter the tactic worked but the 
companies are finding it tough to wean consumers from the cashback 
or lowinterest financing deals 
for the first half of the year chrysler said earnings were down 
637 percent to 251 million fords firsthalf earnings were down 
567 percent to 14 billion and gms were off 465 percent to 16 
billion 
