<TEXT>
federal investigators spread blame widely for 
the exxon valdez oil spill tuesday faulting exxon corp for not 
providing a fit master and a rested and sufficient crew and 
also blaming the captain his third mate the coast guard and local 
authorities 
the national transportation safety board voted 40 in 
determining a fivepart probable cause for the nations worst oil 
spill the dumping of 11 million gallons of crude oil into alaskas 
prince william sound by the grounding of the tanker exxon valdez on 
march 24 1989 
the board said the third mate failed to properly maneuver the 
vessel the alcoholimpaired captain failed to give proper 
supervision exxon failed to provide a crew up to its task the 
coast guard failed in marine traffic control and the state of 
alaska failed to provide adequate piloting rules 
the board concluding a 16month investigation criticized exxon 
valdez capt joseph hazelwood for leaving his third mate gregory 
cousins at the helm before the ship ran aground 
it also said witnesses medical tests and an unusual study of 
hazelwoods speech indicated he was drunk when the ship ran 
aground even though an alaska jury acquitted the captain of being 
intoxicated and the coast guard dropped a drunkenness charge 
hazelwoods attorney thomas russo who attended the board 
meeting said the board members acted like they dropped off the 
moon in accusing hazelwood of being drunk twentyone witnesses 
testified at his trial that he was sober russo said and 
authorities botched blood tests taken more than 10 hours after the 
accident that showed the presence of alcohol 
their conclusions are not founded in the evidence russo 
said 
hazelwood was convicted of one misdemeanor charge of negligent 
discharge of oil he was fined 50000 and ordered to spend 1000 
hours cleaning alaskan beaches he has appealed 
last week the coast guard dismissed charges of drunkenness and 
misconduct against hazelwood but suspended his license as a ships 
master for nine months after he pleaded no contest to breaking 
coast guard rules 
the violations included drinking within four hours before taking 
command of the vessel and leaving the bridge to the other officer 
while the tanker was headed for jagged bligh reef where it split 
open 
board chairman james kolstad said the board hopes its report 
which included 36 safety recommendations will help prevent future 
spills its analysis carries no force of law and by statute 
cannot be used in court cases 
this is the largest and costliest accident the safety board 
has ever investigated said kolstad in opening the meeting he 
said 2 billion had been spent cleaning up the spill 
the boards conclusions included 
the decision by hazelwood to leave his third mate in charge as 
the boat was being maneuvered around a massive ice floe was 
improper and against exxon policies and coast guard rules 
the third mate was impaired by fatigue which contributed to 
his failure to guide the 987foot vessel around the ice 
similar conditions of deck officers with inadequate rest exist 
on other exxon tankers due to a company policy of operating with 
reduced crews 
exxon offers incentives for crews who work long hours and has 
manipulated shipboard reporting of overtime and workload 
the coast guard has been unduly narrow in perspective in 
allowing exxon ships to operate with inadequate crews failing to 
consider the amount of work required in loading the ships before 
they go out to sea 
exxon has no program for dealing with drug and alcohol abuse 
the coast guard is not prepared to take tests for drug and 
alcohol use after accidents 
the transportation departments postaccident testing policies 
are inadequate 
the coast guard should have access to national driving records 
to help it assess the fitness of ships officers to hold federal 
licenses hazelwood had at least two prior convictions for drunken 
driving 
the coast guard should more closely monitor ships and ice 
conditions in prince william sound where its traffic service 
remains ineffective 
limited supervision of the coast guards vessel traffic system 
contributed to the services lack of knowledge that ice was forcing 
ships to move near the reef where the exxon valdez hung up 
two months after the exxon valdez ran aground the board held a 
weeklong public hearing in alaska interviewing 27 witnesses and 
collecting 115 exhibits 
since the spill the tanker has been repaired and renamed the 
exxon mediterranean and has been undergoing tests for service on 
routes in the mediterranean sea or the middle east 
</TEXT>
