a federal regulator said tuesday he would not 
have recommended the taxpayersubsidized sale of 15 texas savings 
and loan associations to an arizona businessman had he known of the 
buyers guilty plea to a fraud charge 
i would have objected george m barclay president of the 
federal home loan bank of dallas told a senate judiciary 
subcommittee having no knowledge of the guilty plea by james fail 
barclay said i was very comfortable with a decision not to 
object to fails purchase of what now is known as bluebonnet 
savings bank 
the sale of the failing sampls is under investigation by the 
business rights subcommittee on three grounds 
evidence that fail put up only 1000 cash for the 15 banks and 
was promised at least 185 billion in federal subsidies sen 
howard metzenbaum dohio chairman of the subcommittee said 3 
billion is a better estimate and called the deal scandalous 
fails plea bargain on one fraud count which resulted in 
dismissal of the indictment and his guilty plea on behalf of his 
united security holding co to another felony charge 
suspicions by metzenbaum that a former aide to thenvice 
president bush improperly intervened with federal officials on 
fails behalf 
that aide robert j thompson refused to testify before the 
subcommittee tuesday because his attorney said the panel has no 
jurisdiction over the banking industry and has systematically 
handed over thompsons private documents to reporters 
the new york times said in wednesday editions that documents 
made available by the committee showed thompson was able to review 
and suggest modifications to government documents affecting his 
clients interests in particular helping officials of the federal 
home loan bank board prepare a response to an inspector generals 
report that found that fail should have been precluded from buying 
the 15 sampls 
metzenbaum said the subcommittee will ask the judiciary 
committee to compel thompson to comply with a subpoena 
my own view is that we should proceed forthwith with the 
strongest means of enforcement of the subpoena said sen arlen 
specter rpa 
stanley m brand thompsons lawyer told the subcommittee 
during the bluebonnet transactions my client simply and 
forthrightly represented his client and scrupulously followed the 
rules and regulations established by duly authorized federal 
regulatory agencies 
thompson said in an interview in the washington post on tuesday 
that in exchange for helping fail he was paid a lobbying fee 
given a 150000 loan and promised 2 percent of profits from 
bluebonnet 
thompson told the post he acted as a project manager helping 
fail work with regulators in washington dallas atlanta and new 
york 
m danny wall former chairman of the federal home loan bank 
board which approved the bluebonnet sale said his records show he 
met only three times with thompson never to discuss the takeover 
stuart d root who at the time of the sale headed the federal 
savings and loan insurance corp said he would not know thompson 
if he walked into the room 
barclay said when the sale was approved in december 1988 he was 
aware that fail and signed a plea bargain that resulted in the 
dropping of a 1976 alabama indictment for securities fraud since 
that offense had occurred more than 10 years in the past it was 
not considered a bar to the sampl purchase 
however barclay added i do not recall having been told 
that an affiliate company of mr fails had pleaded guilty to a 
felony which would have been a presumptive disqualifier 
against fail 
wall rejected allegations that regulators in selling the sampls 
to fail turned down a bid that would have been 97 million better 
for taxpayers 
thats not true at all wall said if the two bids were 
compared on the same basis fails would have been at least equal 
and probably better than the other he said 
